weewx-rtl433-mqtt
Distributed under terms of the GPLv3

This is a driver for weewx that captures rtl_433 events from an MQTT broker.
It is inspired by weewx-sdr (https://github.com/matthewwall/weewx-sdr) but
takes a different approach: rtl_433 runs elsewhere - on a remote host, in a
container, or wherever the SDR dongle lives - and publishes JSON events to
MQTT.  This driver subscribes to those events and feeds them into weewx.

If you want weewx to drive rtl_433 directly via a local USB dongle, use
weewx-sdr instead.  This driver complements it; it does not replace it.


===============================================================================
Architecture

  [SDR host]  rtl_433 -F "mqtt://broker:1883,events"
                          |
                          v
                  [MQTT broker]
                          |
                          | subscribe rtl_433/+/events
                          v
  [weewx host]  user.rtl433mqtt  ->  sensor_map  ->  weewx database

The driver does no demodulation - rtl_433 has already turned the radio
into structured JSON before the message hits the broker.


===============================================================================
Installation

0) install pre-requisites

  a) install weewx
      http://weewx.com/docs
  b) install rtl_433 on the host with the SDR dongle
      https://github.com/merbanan/rtl_433
  c) install paho-mqtt on the weewx host
      pip install paho-mqtt
  d) you need an MQTT broker reachable from both hosts (e.g. mosquitto)

1) install the driver

  weectl extension install /path/to/weewx-rtl433-mqtt

2) configure the driver

  weectl station reconfigure --driver=user.rtl433mqtt --no-prompt

3) start rtl_433 on the SDR host with mqtt output

  rtl_433 -M utc -F "mqtt://BROKER_HOST:1883,events"

  The 'events' suffix tells rtl_433 to publish the full JSON event
  (one publish per detection) to a topic of the form:

    rtl_433/<HOSTNAME>/events

4) verify events are arriving (optional)

  mosquitto_sub -h BROKER_HOST -t 'rtl_433/+/events'

  You should see one JSON line per detected event, e.g.:
    {"time":"2024-01-15 10:23:45","model":"Acurite-Tower","id":11041,
     "channel":"B","battery_ok":1,"temperature_C":22.5,"humidity":45}

5) edit the [RTL433MQTT] section of weewx.conf (see below)

6) start weewx

  sudo systemctl start weewx


===============================================================================
Configuration - the sensor_map

Each entry in [[sensor_map]] maps a weewx database field to a tuple
identifying the source field on a specific sensor:

  <weewx_field> = <rtl_433_field>.<sensor_id>.<rtl_433_model>

For example, an Acurite Tower sensor with id 11041 publishing in metric
mode produces:

  {"model":"Acurite-Tower","id":11041,"temperature_C":22.5,"humidity":45,
   "battery_ok":1}

To map its temperature to outTemp, humidity to outHumidity, and battery
status to outBatteryStatus:

[RTL433MQTT]
    driver = user.rtl433mqtt
    host = mqtt.local
    [[sensor_map]]
        outTemp           = temperature_C.11041.Acurite-Tower
        outHumidity       = humidity.11041.Acurite-Tower
        outBatteryStatus  = battery.11041.Acurite-Tower

NOTE: the field part uses the rtl_433 unit suffix that matches your
unit_system setting.  With unit_system = METRIC (default), use
temperature_C / rain_mm / wind_avg_km_h.  With unit_system = US, the
driver renames those fields automatically, so you map to
temperature_F / rain_in / wind_avg_mi_h.

NOTE: the model part is rtl_433's 'model' field verbatim
(e.g. 'Acurite-Tower' with a hyphen).  This is NOT the same as
weewx-sdr's PacketClassName-style identifier - sensor maps cannot be
copied between the two drivers without translation.

Glob-style patterns work in any of the three components:

    [[sensor_map]]
        outTemp = temperature_C.*.Acurite-Tower


===============================================================================
Configuration - MQTT connection

[RTL433MQTT]
    driver = user.rtl433mqtt
    host = localhost                       # required
    port = 1883                            # default 1883
    topic = rtl_433/+/events               # default
    # username =                           # optional
    # password =                           # optional
    # tls = false                          # optional, default false
    # client_id =                          # optional


===============================================================================
Configuration - unit_system

The driver claims one unit system for every event it produces, so weewx
sees a coherent stream.  rtl_433 mostly emits SI units (_C, _mm, _km_h),
so the default is METRIC and no conversion happens.

If you prefer your weewx configured for US units, set unit_system = US
and the driver will automatically rename and convert any of the following
suffixes on its way out:

    _C    <->  _F     (degrees)
    _mm   <->  _in    (length)
    _km_h <->  _mi_h  (speed)
    _kph  <->  _mph   (speed, alternate label)
    _hPa  <->  _inHg  (pressure)

[RTL433MQTT]
    driver = user.rtl433mqtt
    unit_system = US

A sensor that natively emits a mixed unit set (e.g. _F and _km_h in the
same packet) will produce one converted field and one already-correct
field after this pass; both are exposed.


===============================================================================
Configuration - deltas

Some sensors publish cumulative counters (rain since startup, lifetime
strike count).  WeeWX expects per-period observations.  The [[deltas]]
section indicates which cumulative fields should be split into deltas:

[RTL433MQTT]
    [[deltas]]
        rain                   = rain_total
        lightning_strike_count = strike_count

The default knows about rain and lightning strikes:

    rain                   <- rain_total
    lightning_strike_count <- strike_count

For this to work, the sensor_map must map a cumulative field onto the
right name, e.g.:

    [[sensor_map]]
        rain_total   = rain_mm.0026.Fineoffset-WH1080
        strike_count = strike_count.151.Acurite-6045M


===============================================================================
Configuration - logging

[RTL433MQTT]
    driver = user.rtl433mqtt
    log_unknown_sensors  = false   # log payloads we cannot parse as JSON
    log_unmapped_sensors = false   # log packets that match no sensor_map entry
    log_packets          = true    # log every yielded packet at debug level


===============================================================================
Diagnostics

Subscribe to the broker directly to see exactly what is being published:

  mosquitto_sub -h BROKER_HOST -t 'rtl_433/+/events' -v

Run the driver's standalone mode to see how it parses each event:

  PYTHONPATH=/usr/share/weewx python3 \
      /etc/weewx/bin/user/rtl433mqtt.py \
      --host BROKER_HOST --topic 'rtl_433/+/events'

This prints one 'raw:' line per received event followed by a 'parsed:'
line showing the dict the weewx pipeline would see (including the
<field>.<id>.<model> tagging applied by the driver).  Use this to figure
out the exact strings to put in your sensor_map.
